1) AST with line numbers

Convention (simple, consistent):

Every AST node is a sequence where the first element is the tag string.

The last element of every AST node is the source-line integer for that node.

Declarations & statements each carry the line where they appear.

Example AST for your program (with line numbers 1..4):

-- tags: "Program","VarDecl","Assign","Var","IntLiteral","BinaryOp"
sequence AST = {"Program",
    {
        {"VarDecl","a","integer", 1},
        {"VarDecl","b","integer", 1},
        {"VarDecl","c","integer", 1}
    },
    {
        {"Assign", {"Var","a",2}, {"IntLiteral",1,2}, 2},
        {"Assign", {"Var","b",3}, {"IntLiteral",2,3}, 3},
        {"Assign", {"Var","c",4}, 
            {"BinaryOp", "+", {"Var","a",4}, {"Var","b",4}, 4},
         4}
    },
    1  -- Program node line (optional; we keep it)
}


Notes:

{"Var","a",2} says "variable a referenced at source line 2".

The Assign node carries the line number of the assignment itself (last element).

This makes it trivial to map IR instructions back to exact source lines.

2) IR design that includes explicit debug-display entries

IR instructions are sequences. Standard ops:

{"decl", varname, type, src_line} — declare a source variable (tracked for debug printing).

{"mov", dest, src, src_line} — move a literal/var/temp into dest.

{"add", dest, op1, op2, src_line} — arithmetic (dest <- op1 + op2). (Other ops similar.)

{"dbg", "display", src_line} — explicit debug display: print the declared variables' current values, labelled with this source line.

(You can add {"dbg","break",src_line} for a breakpoint hook if desired.)

Design choices:

Every IR op optionally carries the source line as its last element (useful for mapping).

Debugger display ops appear in the IR only where you (generator) put them — not automatically.

3) AST → IR generator that optionally inserts debug ops

Below is a runnable Phix-like implementation of:

AST→IR that returns {ir, last_result} and uses annotated AST lines.

A small wrapper generate_ir_with_debug(lines_to_display) that inserts {"dbg","display",line} exactly at the points you request.

-- simple temp generator
integer temp_count = 0
function new_temp()
    temp_count += 1
    return sprintf("t%d",{temp_count})
end function

-- ast_to_ir: returns {ir_sequence, result}
-- AST nodes: last element is src_line (int)
function ast_to_ir(sequence node)
    sequence ir = {}
    object result = ""
    string tag = node[1]
    integer node_line = node[$]  -- last element is line number

    switch tag do
        case "Program"
            sequence decls = node[2], body = node[3]
            for i=1 to length(decls) do
                sequence d = decls[i]
                ir &= {{ "decl", d[2], d[3], d[$] }} -- name, type, line
            end for
            for i=1 to length(body) do
                sequence part = ast_to_ir(body[i])
                ir &= part[1]
            end for
            result = ""

        case "Assign"
            -- node = {"Assign", target_node, value_node, line}
            string varname = node[2][2]  -- {"Var", "a", line}
            sequence rhs = ast_to_ir(node[3])
            ir &= rhs[1]
            object rhs_res = rhs[2]
            -- emit mov with src_line = assign's line
            ir &= {{ "mov", varname, rhs_res, node_line }}
            result = varname

        case "Var"
            -- simply return the variable name (no code)
            result = node[2]

        case "IntLiteral"
            result = node[2]  -- literal value

        case "BinaryOp"
            string op = node[2]
            sequence left = ast_to_ir(node[3])
            sequence right = ast_to_ir(node[4])
            ir &= left[1] & right[1]
            string lres = left[2]
            string rres = right[2]
            string t = new_temp()
            string ir_op = iff(op="+","add", op) -- support more ops easily
            ir &= {{ ir_op, t, lres, rres, node_line }}
            result = t

        case else
            crash("Unknown AST tag: " & tag)
    end switch

    return {ir, result}
end function

-- convenience wrapper that generates IR and inserts dbg displays at chosen lines
function generate_ir_with_debug(sequence ast, sequence lines_to_display)
    temp_count = 0
    sequence gen = ast_to_ir(ast)
    sequence raw_ir = gen[1]

    -- Build final IR inserting dbg entries when we pass instructions whose src_line matches
    sequence final_ir = {}
    for i=1 to length(raw_ir) do
        sequence ins = raw_ir[i]
        final_ir &= {ins}
        -- ins's last element is the src_line (we ensured it above for ops)
        integer ins_line = ins[$]
        -- if this line is in the user-requested list, insert dbg display
        for j=1 to length(lines_to_display) do
            if lines_to_display[j] = ins_line then
                final_ir &= {{ "dbg", "display", ins_line }}
                break
            end if
        end for
    end for

    return final_ir
end function


Notes:

generate_ir_with_debug(AST, {2,3,4}) will insert {"dbg","display",2} etc right after the IR instruction whose src_line is that line. This gives precise control.

You can also choose to insert the dbg op before the instruction if you prefer to show the pre state for that line (adjust placement accordingly).

4) IR interpreter / debugger that prints only declared source variables

We will:

initialize env with declared source vars (from decl ops).

treat temporaries as normal entries in env but hide them in debugger prints.

dbg display will print exactly the declared variables (in declaration order) with their current values and the source line.

include map.e
map env
sequence declared_order = {}  -- keep order of source declarations

procedure init_env_from_ir(sequence ir)
    env = new()
    declared_order = {}
    for i=1 to length(ir) do
        sequence ins = ir[i]
        if ins[1] = "decl" then
            map:put(env, ins[2], "novalue")
            declared_order &= {ins[2]}
        end if
    end for
end procedure

-- lookup: if operand is a name and exists in env, return its value;
-- if it's a literal number, return it. We assume constants are numeric values, not strings.
function lookup_operand(object op)
    if type(op) = "sequence" then
        crash("unexpected sequence in lookup")
    end if
    if string(op) then
        if map:has(env, op) then
            return map:get(env, op)
        else
            -- could be a temporary not seen before: default novalue
            return map:get(env, op, "novalue") -- map:get with default (if implemented)
        end if
    else
        -- numeric literal
        return op
    end if
end function

procedure exec_ir_with_debug(sequence ir)
    init_env_from_ir(ir)
    for i=1 to length(ir) do
        sequence ins = ir[i]
        string op = ins[1]

        if op = "decl" then
            -- already handled in init_env

        elsif op = "mov" then
            string dest = ins[2]
            object src = ins[3]
            object val = lookup_operand(src)
            map:put(env, dest, val)

        elsif op = "add" then
            string dest = ins[2]
            object v1 = lookup_operand(ins[3])
            object v2 = lookup_operand(ins[4])
            map:put(env, dest, v1 + v2)

        elsif op = "dbg" and ins[2] = "display" then
            integer ln = ins[3]
            -- print the declared variables only, in declared order
            printf(1,"[line %d] ",{ln})
            for k=1 to length(declared_order) do
                string name = declared_order[k]
                object v = map:get(env,name)
                printf(1,"%s = %v  ",{name, v})
            end for
            puts(1,"\n")

        else
            crash("Unknown IR op: " & op)
        end if
    end for
end procedure

5) Example: full flow for your tiny program

Generate IR with debug displays at lines 1..4 (or exactly where you want):

sequence IR = generate_ir_with_debug(AST, {1,2,3,4})
? IR
exec_ir_with_debug(IR)


Expected final IR (example):

{
 {"decl","a","integer",1},
 {"dbg","display",1},           -- if you asked to display line 1
 {"decl","b","integer",1},
 {"decl","c","integer",1},

 {"mov","a",1,2},
 {"dbg","display",2},           -- show state after line 2
 {"mov","b",2,3},
 {"dbg","display",3},
 {"add","t1","a","b",4},
 {"mov","c","t1",4},
 {"dbg","display",4}
}


Example debugger output (if you asked to display lines 1–4):

[line 1] a = novalue  b = novalue  c = novalue
[line 2] a = 1         b = novalue  c = novalue
[line 3] a = 1         b = 2         c = novalue
[line 4] a = 1         b = 2         c = 3


You control precisely where the output appears by selecting which source lines to insert {"dbg","display",line} for.

6) Register allocation strategy for this IR

For a small IR like ours, a practical approach is Linear Scan Register Allocation — simple, fast, and very suitable for JITs and small compilers. Here’s a compact plan tailored to your IR:

a) Compute live ranges

Walk the IR and assign each instruction a sequential index (position).

For each temporary or variable (every name that is not a declared source variable or a physical register), record:

the first position it is defined (def),

the last position it is used (last use).

For source-level variables you plan to keep in memory (e.g., addressable locals), you may choose to treat loads/stores to/from registers as operations (coalescing later).

b) Linear-scan allocation

Sort live ranges by increasing start position.

Maintain a set active of variables currently assigned to registers, ordered by increasing end position.

Have R physical registers available (e.g., R = 4 or 8).

For each live interval i in start order:

Expire old intervals: remove any j from active where j.end < i.start (free those registers).

If active.size < R: assign a free register to i and insert i into active (sorted by end).

Else: pick k in active with the largest end. If k.end > i.end:

spill k (move it to stack), assign k's register to i, replace k with i in active.

else: spill i (give it a stack slot; will load when needed).

Spilling policy: choose the interval with the farthest next use or largest end (as above).

When spilling, insert load/store IR pseudo-ops around uses/defs (or mark that lowering stage must do it).

c) Coalescing and mov-elision

After initial allocation, coalesce copy moves (mov a b) by trying to assign a and b the same register if their lifetimes don’t conflict.

If mov becomes a no-op (same register), remove it.

d) Handling source variables vs temporaries

Two strategies:

Keep source variables in memory (stack slots) by default, load into registers when used and store on writes; treats temps as register candidates only. Simpler.

Try to allocate registers to source variables as well (treat them like temps), keeping a home slot for spilled vars. This reduces loads/stores but requires more careful spills.

For your debugger-aware IR, I recommend:

Treat temporaries (t1, t2, ...) as primary register allocation targets.

Treat declared source variables as memory-backed (stack slot) but allow coalescing:

If a mov, dest, src moves a temp into a source variable and they never overlap, you may allocate the temp into the same register and just emit a store at the end — reduces stores.

Remember: since the debugger wants to show source variables at dbg display points, you must ensure the memory slots for source variables are updated before a dbg display. 
That may force stores right before dbg display if you held the current value only in a register. 
(Or change debugger to read register state — but that couples the debugger to register allocator.)

e) Example for the tiny program

Live ranges:

a defined at mov (pos 4); used later at add (pos 6) and then maybe live at program end.

b similar.

t1 created for add: start at add pos, end at mov to c.

With 2 registers (R0,R1): you could place a in R0, b in R1, t1 needs a register but you can reuse R0 or R1 after their last uses 
- simple linear-scan will find that t1 can use R0 after the last use of a.

f) Additional advanced options

Build SSA form before allocation: makes interference and coalescing easier, improves allocation quality.

Use graph coloring for better global allocation (but it's more complex).

Interleave register allocation with instruction selection for best outcomes on constrained architectures.

7) Practical tips & debugger integration

Because you insert {"dbg","display",line} in the IR, the register allocator must ensure that the memory locations read by the debugger are up-to-date at that point. Two practical options:

Force a store-before-debug: whenever an allocated register holds a source variable value, and you hit a dbg display, emit stores to the variable's stack slot before the dbg op. 
Simple but can cause extra stores.

Let the debugger read register state: if your runtime exposes register values to the debugger, you can read registers directly — more complex but avoids stores.

For an AST-level single-stepping debugger, keep both representations: AST (for pretty printing, breakpoints on source lines) and IR (for execution / optimisation). 
You already have line numbers in AST and in IR ops so mapping is trivial.

