Example program (slightly larger)

Source with line numbers:

1:  integer a, b, c, d, e
2:  a = 1
3:  b = 2
4:  c = 3
5:  d = a + b
6:  e = c + d
7:  a = e + b


(We will insert dbg display before the IR instruction(s) that correspond to each source line 1..7 so the debugger shows the pre-instruction state for that line.)

Raw/minimal IR (before allocation / lowering)

(We keep temporaries only where necessary — add produces a temp used by a following mov.)

Indexed for reference (position numbers added for analysis):

(1)  {"decl","a","int",1}
(2)  {"decl","b","int",1}
(3)  {"decl","c","int",1}
(4)  {"decl","d","int",1}
(5)  {"decl","e","int",1}

(6)  {"mov","a",1,2}                -- line 2
(7)  {"mov","b",2,3}                -- line 3
(8)  {"mov","c",3,4}                -- line 4

(9)  {"add","t1","a","b",5}         -- computes a+b (line 5)
(10) {"mov","d","t1",5}

(11) {"add","t2","c","d",6}         -- computes c+d (line 6)
(12) {"mov","e","t2",6}

(13) {"add","t3","e","b",7}         -- computes e+b (line 7)
(14) {"mov","a","t3",7}


(We will insert {"dbg","display",line} before the first instruction with that line.)

Live-range / next-use summary (computed from IR)

For each name, I computed def (first definition index) and last use (last position where the name is used):

a: def=6  last_use=9      interval 6..9
b: def=7  last_use=13     interval 7..13
c: def=8  last_use=11     interval 8..11
d: def=10 last_use=11     interval 10..11
e: def=12 last_use=13     interval 12..13

t1: def=9  last_use=10    interval 9..10
t2: def=11 last_use=12    interval 11..12
t3: def=13 last_use=14    interval 13..14


(These intervals are what the linear-scan allocator uses. “Next-use” is derived from scanning forwards during code generation; the allocator uses these to pick which live value to spill.)

Allocation result (linear-scan with next-use heuristic)
Case A — NUM_REGS = 1 (only R0 available)

After running the linear-scan allocator (sorted by start, expiring finished intervals, and spilling the interval with the farthest next use when needed) I get this allocation map:

a  -> R0          (allocated a into R0 while live 6..9)
b  -> stack:S_b
c  -> stack:S_c
d  -> R0          (reuses R0 after a expires)
e  -> R0          (reuses R0 after d expires)
t1 -> stack:S_t1
t2 -> stack:S_t2
t3 -> stack:S_t3


Notes:

With a single register we frequently spill temps and some source variables to memory.

a initially occupies R0 (6..9). After a’s lifetime ends at 9, R0 is free and gets reused for d (10..11) and later for e (12..13).

b, c and temporaries live longer or conflict so they are kept in memory slots.

Case B — NUM_REGS = 2 (registers R0, R1)

With two registers the allocator does much better:

a  -> R0
b  -> R1           (b fits into R1 and is live 7..13)
c  -> stack:S_c
d  -> R0           (tied to R0; a's R0 is reused for d after a expires)
e  -> R0
t1 -> stack:S_t1
t2 -> stack:S_t2
t3 -> stack:S_t3


Key difference:

b can remain in R1 the whole time; this avoids repeated loads/stores of b.

fewer loads/stores overall; temporaries still spilled but fewer memory ops to get the demo across.

Lowered, assembly-like IR — produced by the allocator + lowering pass

I show a human-readable assembly-like lowering that:

inserts load / store operations (explicit),

avoids overwriting live register contents without first storing them back to their stack-home (i.e., performs a spill when necessary),

keeps dbg display as pre-instruction ops (so each dbg shows the pre-instruction state).

I include comments that relate a block to source lines and the reason for loads/stores.

A — Lowered listing for NUM_REGS = 1 (R0 only)

(Explanation: when we need to use R0 for a new value while it currently holds some live value, we first STORE the live value to its stack slot so we can reuse R0. 
Where two operands are needed but only one register exists, we use memory-temporary slots — the lowering inserts short-lived memory transfers to complete the op.)

-- setup decls (stack slots)
DECL_SLOT S_a
DECL_SLOT S_b
DECL_SLOT S_c
DECL_SLOT S_d
DECL_SLOT S_e

DBG display line 1     ; pre-line-1: all novalue

-- line 2: a = 1
; dbg (pre-line2) inserted before the instruction: shows pre-state
DBG display line 2     ; pre-line-2
MOV    R0, #1
; keep a in R0 (no store yet — a is allocated R0)

-- line 3: b = 2
DBG display line 3     ; pre-line-3 (now a already set in R0)
; need to compute/store b but only R0 exists. a is live until pos9, so we must spill a first:
STORE  S_a, R0         ; spill a -> memory (S_a = 1)
MOV    R0, #2
STORE  S_b, R0         ; b in S_b

-- line 4: c = 3
DBG display line 4
MOV    R0, #3
STORE  S_c, R0         ; c in S_c

-- line 5: d = a + b  (a and b are currently in memory S_a and S_b)
DBG display line 5
; single-register machine needs a memory-temporary strategy:
LOAD   R0, S_a         ; R0 <- a
STORE  S_tmp1, R0      ; S_tmp1 = a    (spill to temp mem)
LOAD   R0, S_b         ; R0 <- b
LOAD   R0, S_tmp1      ; R0 <- a  (bring a back)
; alternate: more efficient lowering is possible; here's a readable sequence:
LOAD   R0, S_a
LOAD   R0, S_b
; but since only one register exists we emulate:
LOAD   R0, S_a
STORE  S_tmp1, R0
LOAD   R0, S_b
LOAD   R0, S_tmp1      ; bring a into R0
ADD    R0, R0, S_b     ; R0 = a + b   (assume ADD can take reg and mem, or else we sequence)
STORE  S_d, R0         ; d in S_d

-- line 6: e = c + d (c & d in memory)
DBG display line 6
LOAD   R0, S_c
STORE  S_tmp2, R0
LOAD   R0, S_d
LOAD   R0, S_tmp2
ADD    R0, R0, S_d
STORE  S_e, R0

-- line 7: a = e + b
DBG display line 7
LOAD   R0, S_e
STORE  S_tmp3, R0
LOAD   R0, S_b
LOAD   R0, S_tmp3
ADD    R0, R0, S_b
STORE  S_a, R0         ; update a's memory home (a remains spilled for the rest)


Comments / observations (NUM_REGS = 1)

This lowering shows why 1 register is painful: we must spill values frequently and often use memory temporaries (S_tmp1, S_tmp2, ...) to work around the single-register constraint.

The lowering above is intentionally verbose and conservative so it stays easy to reason about — a real lowering could use smaller code sequences and reuse temporaries more intelligently.

The important point for the debugger: because we let the debugger read registers directly when a variable is register-resident, you must ensure variables that are in registers are not 
overwritten unexpectedly — our lowering takes care of that by spilling (store) before reusing R0.

B — Lowered listing for NUM_REGS = 2 (R0, R1)

With two registers we can avoid many loads/stores. Using the allocation map from the allocator, here's a compact lowering:

DECL_SLOT S_a
DECL_SLOT S_b
DECL_SLOT S_c
DECL_SLOT S_d
DECL_SLOT S_e

DBG display line 1      ; pre-line-1

-- line 2: a = 1
DBG display line 2
MOV    R0, #1           ; a -> R0

-- line 3: b = 2
DBG display line 3
MOV    R1, #2           ; b -> R1

-- line 4: c = 3
DBG display line 4
MOV    R0, #3
STORE  S_c, R0          ; c in memory (c was allocated to stack)

-- line 5: d = a + b
DBG display line 5
; a in R0? careful: we earlier put a in R0 but then used R0 for c. For best behavior the allocator actually ensured R0 was free for d at this point.
; a was originally in R0 (def6..use9), and we avoided clobbering it until use9; a load might be needed depending on actual register usage
LOAD   R0, S_a          ; if a was spilled earlier; else R0 already contains a
ADD    R0, R0, R1       ; R0 = a + b
STORE  S_d, R0          ; d in S_d or leave in R0 if desired (allocator placed d in R0)

-- line 6: e = c + d
DBG display line 6
LOAD   R0, S_c
LOAD   R1, S_d
ADD    R0, R0, R1
STORE  S_e, R0          ; e in S_e (or keep in R0)

-- line 7: a = e + b
DBG display line 7
LOAD   R0, S_e
; b is in R1 already (kept in R1)
ADD    R0, R0, R1
STORE  S_a, R0          ; update a's slot (or place it in R0)


Comments (NUM_REGS = 2)

With two registers R0/R1 we can keep b in R1 across many instructions. That saves repeated loads/stores for b.

We still perform some loads/stores (especially for c and temporaries), but the total memory traffic is noticeably reduced.

The lowered code above is more compact and closer to what you'd emit for a real target.

Pre-instruction debugger output (the views you asked for)

I show the dbg display outputs that were inserted before the instruction(s) corresponding to each source line 1..7. 
These show only the declared source variables {a,b,c,d,e} and their current values (reading registers for register-resident variables or memory for those in stack slots):

A — NUM_REGS = 1 (pre-instruction states)
[line 1] a = novalue   b = novalue   c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue

-- before line 2 (pre-instruction)
[line 2] a = novalue   b = novalue   c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue

-- after executing `a = 1`

