-- after executing `a = e + b` final state (post-line7) would be:
a = 8, b = 2, c = 3, d = 3, e = 6


Notes:

These lines are the pre-instruction prints. For each source line N the debugger printed the program state just before executing the instruction(s) of line N.

The post-state comments are shown as context so you can see what happens after the line executes; your debugger will be showing only the pre-states (as requested).

B — NUM_REGS = 2 (pre-instruction states)

The pre-instruction values are identical from the point of view of the high-level program — the difference is internal (fewer loads/stores). So the debugger pre-prints are the same:

[line 1] a = novalue   b = novalue   c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue
[line 2] a = novalue   b = novalue   c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue
[line 3] a = 1         b = novalue   c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue
[line 4] a = 1         b = 2         c = novalue   d = novalue   e = novalue
[line 5] a = 1         b = 2         c = 3         d = novalue   e = novalue
[line 6] a = 1         b = 2         c = 3         d = 3         e = novalue
[line 7] a = 1         b = 2         c = 3         d = 3         e = 6


(Again, those are pre-instruction prints; the final post-line7 state would be a=8 etc.)

Remarks about accuracy & approximations

I kept the IR lowering conservative and explicit so it is easy to follow. A production lowering could be tighter 
(avoid creating many S_tmp slots; schedule loads/stores to reuse registers better).

For the NUM_REGS=1 lowering I used memory-temporary sequences to cope with needing two operand values with only one register — that is correct conceptually 
but the exact sequence depends on what your micro code supports (e.g., whether ADD can accept a memory operand directly). You can adapt those sequences to your target ISA style.

The linear-scan allocator I used uses the standard approach:

compute intervals (start,end),

iterate intervals in increasing start,

expire intervals that ended,

if registers free, allocate one,

else pick interval with farthest end to spill (or spill current).

lowering then inserts loads/stores accordingly and uses a spilled interval's register for the new interval when possible.

Important debugger note: because you wanted the debugger to sometimes read registers directly (which avoids forcing stores), the allocator and lowering must both 
maintain the allocation_map and keep the runtime aware of which variables are in registers vs memory at the dbg points. My lowered listings are written respecting 
that policy (we inserted STORE operations before clobbering registers so pre-dbg sees the correct values).

