regs: R0=novalue R1=novalue

instr 7 dbg display 2 → [line 2] a..e = novalue

instr 8 mov R0,#1 → R0=1 (a in R0)

instr 9 dbg display 3 → [line 3] a=1 b=novalue c..=novalue

instr 10 mov R1,#2 → R1=2 (b in R1)

instr 11 dbg display 4 → [line 4] a=1 b=2 c=novalue ...

instr 12 mov R0,#3 → R0=3

instr 13 store S_c,R0 → S_c=3 (we stored c to memory; note: this clobbered R0 which previously held a; allocator ensured a's lifetime allowed reuse)

instr 14 dbg display 5 → [line 5] a=1 b=2 c=3 d=novalue e=novalue

instr 15 load R0,S_a → R0 = (a) = 1 (if a was in reg earlier this might be a no-op)

instr 16 add R0,R0,R1 → R0 = 1 + 2 = 3

instr 17 store S_d,R0 → S_d = 3

instr 18 dbg display 6 → [line 6] a=1 b=2 c=3 d=3 e=novalue

instr 19 load R0,S_c → R0 = 3

instr 20 load R1,S_d → R1 = 3 (overwrites b=2 if allocator spilled b; but in this allocation we kept b in R1, so this load may be unnecessary -- lowering conservatively loads)

instr 21 add R0,R0,R1 → R0 = 3 + 3 = 6

instr 22 store S_e,R0 → S_e = 6

instr 23 dbg display 7 → [line 7] a=1 b=2 c=3 d=3 e=6

instr 24 load R0,S_e → R0 = 6

instr 25 add R0,R0,R1 → R0 = 6 + 2 = 8 (assuming R1 still holds b=2; if R1 was overwritten earlier we would have reloaded it)

instr 26 store S_a,R0 → S_a = 8

Final post-line7 program state:

a=8, b=2, c=3, d=3, e=6


Observations & comparison

With 2 registers the runtime produced far fewer loads/stores and the register file captured long-lived b in R1 so add ops were fast.

The dbg display outputs are identical at source-level pre-instruction points (because they show source variables). What's improved is fewer memory moves and cleaner lowered IR.

The allocator + lowering respected the requirement that dbg display reads the current value (reading registers when allocation maps the variable to a register).

